
0 — Project scaffold & shared styles
Create a local-first browser tool suite. No backend, no signup, no tracking.
Project structure (all files in one flat folder):
  styles.css          — site-wide base (dark theme CSS variables, card, container, grid, footer)
  image-resize.css    — extended component library shared across all pages:
                         drop-zone, kb-presets, loader+spinner, preview-wrap,
                         resize-hero header, format-mode tab bar, button styles,
                         status tones (info/success/warn/error via data-tone attribute)
  site-sw.js          — service worker: precaches shell assets, cache-first for CDN
                         models (MediaPipe, heic2any, jsPDF, fast-xml-parser)
Design:
  - Dark theme — background #0f172a, card #1e293b, elevated #273549,
    accent #6366f1, border rgba(148,163,184,0.12)
  - CSS custom properties for all colours, radius, spacing
  - Fully responsive (single-column < 768 px, side-by-side >= 768 px)
  - Accessible: ARIA labels, keyboard nav, focus rings, aria-live regions
  - Each page adds a `page-*` body class and a hero header with eyebrow + H1 + lead copy
  - Footer: Privacy · About · Contact links
  - "Other tools" link-grid card at the bottom of every page
Deliverables: styles.css, image-resize.css, site-sw.js only.
1 — Image resize by file size
Build image-resize.html (+ app.js + worker.js).
Feature: resize any image so its JPEG output lands at a user-specified
kilobyte target. All processing is local — no upload.
Supported input: JPG, PNG, WebP, HEIC/HEIF (via heic2any CDN shim).
UI elements:
  - Drag-and-drop zone with SVG upload icon; click to browse
  - Visually-hidden <input type=file>; show selected filename in a .file-row
  - KB target <input type=number> with placeholder "e.g. 200"
  - Quick-preset buttons for 50 / 100 / 200 / 500 KB
  - "Resize" primary button, "Reset" secondary button
  - Loader: inline spinner + text ("Resizing…")
  - Preview column: shows output image; placeholder silhouette when empty
  - Status <p> with data-tone=info/success/warn/error
  - "Other tools" card linking to the other pages in the suite
worker.js (Web Worker, plain script):
  - Receives { imageBitmap, targetKB, quality }
  - Binary-search JPEG quality (8 iterations, lo=0.4 hi=0.97) to hit targetKB
  - Returns { blob, sizeBytes, width, height }
app.js (ES module, type=module):
  - initPage() wires all events
  - decodeAnyImage(file): tries createImageBitmap first; HEIC fallback via heic2any
  - applyExifOrientation(bitmap, orientation): transform matrix shim
  - updatePreview(blob): draw on <canvas>, show dimensions + KB
  - setupKbPresets(): click handler sets the number input
  - setStatus(msg, type): updates #status data-tone
  - toggleLoading(bool): show/hide spinner, disable primary button
Use: heic2any@0.0.3 from unpkg (UMD global, loaded in <head>).
2 — Compress image (compress-image.html)
Build compress-image.html. Reuse app.js and worker.js from the resize tool.
Difference from resize: the user sets a quality slider (0–100) instead of
a KB target. The slider is labelled "Quality" with a live numeric readout.
Output format selector: Original / JPEG / WebP / PNG.
The same drop-zone, preview, status, and loader components are reused from
image-resize.css.
New options panel items:
  - <input type=range id=quality min=0 max=100 value=85>
  - <output id=qualityVal>85</output> synced in real time
  - <select id=outputFormat> with four options
Worker: same binary but receives { imageBitmap, quality, format } and returns
{blob, sizeBytes, width, height}. No binary search.
Page shares the page-resize body class for styling.
3 — Images & documents to PDF
Build convert-to-pdf.html (+ images-to-pdf.js). No backend.
Supported inputs (multiple files at once):
  Images: JPG, PNG, WebP, HEIC
  Documents: .txt plain text, .docx (via mammoth.js lazy-loaded from CDN)
UI:
  - Multi-file drop zone (accept="image/*,.heic,.heif,.txt,.docx")
  - File list with per-file status icons (✓ image / ✓ doc / ✗ unsupported)
  - "Image quality in PDF" range slider 0.5–1.0, default 0.85
  - "Convert to PDF" primary button, "Clear all" secondary
  - Loader spinner + status message
  - Auto-download of PDF on success
PDF logic (images-to-pdf.js, ES module):
  - Use jsPDF (UMD from unpkg) — window.jspdf.jsPDF
  - For each image: decode → createImageBitmap → draw on OffscreenCanvas →
    convertToBlob(JPEG, quality) → embed in PDF page sized to the image
  - HEIC: decode via heic2any first
  - .docx: await ensureMammoth() lazy-loads mammoth.browser.min.js from unpkg,
    then extractRawText({arrayBuffer}) → add as a text page in jsPDF
  - .txt: FileReader → text → jsPDF.splitTextToSize → addPage + text
  - Pages sized to content; portrait A4 for documents, image native for photos
Info card beneath the tool listing file-size limits and what formats are supported.
Reuses page-resize body class and image-resize.css components.
4 — XML / JSON / XSD format converter
Build format-convert.html (+ format-convert.js + xsd-sample-xml.js).
Three conversion modes (tab bar):
  XML → JSON   |   JSON → XML   |   XSD → Sample XML
Layout: two-panel editor (source left, result right) with a narrow options
sidebar on the far right. Container max-width 1400 px (wider than other pages).
Common editor features:
  - <textarea> for source and result, monospace font
  - Live stats: line count · character count · KB
  - Drag-and-drop a file onto either textarea to load it
  - Action bar: Convert (primary) · Format · Swap · Copy · Download · Clear
  - Keyboard shortcut: Ctrl/Cmd+Enter triggers Convert
  - Status bar with data-tone=info/success/warn/error
XML→JSON options sidebar:
  - "Ignore attributes" checkbox
  - "Compact output" checkbox (no indent)
JSON→XML options sidebar:
  - "Root element name" text input (default "root")
  - "Indent spaces" number input (default 2)
XSD→Sample XML options sidebar:
  - Root element <select> (populated by parsing the XSD)
  - Badge showing "N global elements" or "N global complexTypes"
  - "Include optional elements" checkbox (default on)
  - "Max depth" number input (default 20)
  - "Indent spaces" number input (default 2)
  - "XML declaration" checkbox
  - "Max occurrences samples" number input (default 1)
  - "Generate all global elements" toggle checkbox
    → when on: hide root selector, show Wrapper tag + Max elements inputs
    → when off: show root selector, hide wrapper inputs
Libraries: fast-xml-parser from esm.sh (ESM import in format-convert.js).
xsd-sample-xml.js (ES module, exported):
  listRootEntries(xsdString) → Array<{name, kind:"element"|"complexType", abstract}>
  listRootElements(xsdString) → string[]  (backward-compat)
  generateSampleXmlFromXsd(xsdString, options) → string
  generateAllRootsXml(xsdString, options) → string
Schema support in xsd-sample-xml.js:
  - xs: / xsd: / no-prefix schemas via namespace-agnostic isEl()
  - Global xs:element and (fallback) global xs:complexType roots
  - xs:complexType: sequence, all, choice, group ref, attributeGroup ref
  - xs:simpleContent extension/restriction (text node + attributes)
  - xs:complexContent extension/restriction (inheritance chain)
  - xs:simpleType: restriction (enumeration first value), list, union
  - xs:attribute (required/optional/prohibited), use="required"
  - xs:any → <!-- xs:any placeholder --> comment
  - abstract="true" elements skipped (filtered from root list)
  - Cycle detection via ctx.expanding Set keyed on tag name
  - targetNamespace injected on root element as xmlns=""
  - Built-in XSD types → realistic sample values
  - External / XBRL / ISO 20022 type heuristics map (EXT_TYPE_SAMPLES)
  - generateAllRootsXml wraps all roots in a configurable <WrapperTag>
    with optional element cap and truncation comment
5 — Passport photo maker
Build passport-photo.html (+ passport-photo.js + passport-photo-worker.js
+ passport-photo-presets.js + passport-photo.css + passport-photo-sw.js).
Purpose: browser-only passport photo generator. No upload. No server.
Presets (passport-photo-presets.js, exported PRESETS map):
  us_passport    — 2×2 in (50.8×50.8 mm), 300 DPI, white bg, 54–10240 KB
  india_passport — 35×45 mm, 300 DPI, white bg, 10–1024 KB
  india_visa     — 2×2 in square, 300 DPI, white bg, 10–300 KB
  Each preset has: photo{widthMm, heightMm, dpi},
  head{minRatio, maxRatio, targetRatio},
  eyeLine{min/max/targetFromBottomRatio},
  background{hex, tolerance},
  fileSize{minKB, maxKB, preferredKB},
  output{format, quality}
UI layout (page-resize layout, two columns):
  Left column (controls):
    - Preset tab bar (US Passport / India Passport / India Visa)
    - Preset summary line (dimensions, DPI, file-size range)
    - Drop zone for photo (JPG/PNG/WebP/HEIC, max 25 MB)
    - File name display row
    - Options section:
        "Replace background" checkbox + hint
        Background colour: <input type=color> + <select> preset
        "Auto-crop using face detection" checkbox + hint
        Target file size KB (optional number input + hint)
    - Primary "Generate photo" button + "Start over" secondary
    - Loader (spinner + text), progress bar, status paragraph
    - Compliance checklist (aria-live, hidden until generated)
  Right column (preview):
    - Preview canvas (hidden until generated)
    - Crop overlay (auto-opens after upload):
        - <canvas id=cropCanvas> painted with working bitmap
        - Dim overlay with CSS mask cutout showing the crop area
        - Crop rect div with 4 corner drag handles
        - Dashed "Eye line" guide at preset's targetFromBottomRatio
        - Hint text with "Reset to auto" link
    - Photo metadata (px × px · mm × mm @ DPI · KB)
    - Download row (hidden until generated):
        Download photo (JPG)  |  Download 4×6 print sheet (PDF)
        Adjust crop & regenerate link
passport-photo.js (ES module, main thread):
  CRITICAL: face detection and background segmentation both run here
  (not in worker) because MediaPipe owns its own WebGL context.
  loadVision():
    - Dynamic import of vision_bundle.mjs from cdn.jsdelivr.net/@mediapipe/tasks-vision@0.10.14
    - Falls back to +esm URL if primary fails
    - FilesetResolver.forVisionTasks(wasm base URL)
    - Shared by face detector AND segmenter (one import, one fileset)
  ensureFaceDetector({silent}):
    - FaceDetector.createFromOptions, model: blaze_face_short_range float16
    - minDetectionConfidence: 0.3 (generous for passport-style photos)
    - Caches in state.faceDetector
    - On failure: sets state.faceModelError and throws
  detectFaces(bitmap):
    - Pass 1: detect on downscaled copy (≤ 1024 px)
    - Pass 2: if 0 found, retry at full working-bitmap resolution
    - Returns { faces: Array, modelError: string|null }
    - Each face: { box:{x,y,w,h}, leftEye, rightEye, score }
  ensureSegmenter({silent}):
    - ImageSegmenter.createFromOptions, model: selfie_segmenter float16
    - outputConfidenceMasks: true
    - Caches in state.segmenter
  replaceBackground(srcBitmap, bgHex):
    - Downscale to ≤ 1536 px for segmenter
    - Call segmenter.segment(), get confidenceMasks[0]
    - 3×3 box-blur the Float32 mask to suppress edge speckle
    - Composite at full srcBitmap resolution using bilinear mask sampling
    - Smoothstep alpha curve (LO=0.30, HI=0.70, cubic Hermite t²(3-2t))
    - Returns new ImageBitmap with background replaced
  handleFile(file):
    - Validate size (≤ 25 MB)
    - decodeAnyImage: createImageBitmap with imageOrientation:"from-image",
      HEIC fallback via heic2any
    - applyExifOrientation shim (for non-standard decoders)
    - downscaleBitmap to WORKING_MAX_DIM_PX = 2000
    - detectFaces → state.faces + state.faceModelError
    - Set appropriate status message
    - openCropOverlay() automatically
  runPipeline():
    - Read live crop rect from state.crop.rect (user's current view IS the crop)
    - If removeBackground: call replaceBackground(); surface model error if failed
    - Clone bitmap, postMessage to worker (transferable)
    - On result: displayResult()
  Crop overlay (openCropOverlay / closeCropOverlay):
    - Opens automatically after upload
    - Closes automatically when result is ready (show preview instead)
    - "Adjust crop & regenerate" re-opens with last rect preserved
    - Crop rect initialised from autoCropRectForUI (mirrors worker crop calc)
    - Pointer drag: move + aspect-locked resize via 4 corner handles
    - Arrow-key nudge (1 px normal, 10 px with Shift)
    - applyRectToDom: positions rect + updates SVG mask + eye-line guide
    - onCropWindowResize: repaints canvas + repositions overlay
  buildPrintSheetPdf():
    - Uses jsPDF (UMD, window.jspdf.jsPDF)
    - Fits copies of the passport photo on a 4×6 inch sheet
    - Calculates cols/rows from sheet dimensions and photo size
    - Draws cut-line rects; footer text with preset info
passport-photo-worker.js (module worker):
  - Receives already-composited bitmap (bg replaced on main thread)
  - safeBitmapToCanvas → OffscreenCanvas (defensive copy)
  - Crop: priority = user cropOverride > face auto-crop > centre crop
  - autoCropRectFromFace: headPx = box.h * 1.55; photoH = headPx / head.targetRatio
  - Render exact targetWPx × targetHPx canvas at 300 DPI
  - encodeToTargetSize:
      Default target = preset.preferredKB (hits middle of allowed band)
      Binary search JPEG quality (9 iterations)
      If still < minKB: retry quality 1.0
      If still < minKB: APP15 padding (padJpegToMinSize) — JPEG marker
        that every decoder ignores, used to satisfy strict minimum-size portals
  - setJpegDpi: patch or insert JFIF APP0 with DPI=300
  - Build small preview PNG (≤ 600 px) for fast display
  - Return { jpegBuffer, previewBuffer, widthPx, heightPx, dpi, sizeBytes }
passport-photo-sw.js:
  - Cache name: passport-photo-models-v2
  - Cache-first for cdn.jsdelivr.net and storage.googleapis.com
  - Path hints: @mediapipe/tasks-vision, blaze_face_short_range,
    selfie_segmenter, .tflite, .wasm
  - On activate: delete caches that don't match current version
Compliance checks (rendered after generation):
  - File size vs preset min/max (pass/warn/fail)
  - Face count (1=pass, 0=warn with faceModelError context, 2+=fail)
  - Face confidence (≥ 0.85=pass, lower=warn)
  - Background replaced (pass/fail with actual error if model failed)
  - Output dimensions @ DPI (always pass)
Tips & limitations section (below the tool card):
  - Two-column "Use / Avoid" table with ✓/✗ icons
  - 9-item "Limitations" list with amber alert icons covering:
    quality not graded, rules not enforced, segmentation approximate,
    axis-aligned crop, alignment can miss, no ICC profiles,
    first-load needs internet, low-RAM devices may struggle,
    compliance checks are necessary but not sufficient
6 — Recreating with Claude's extended thinking
When you open a new conversation with the claude-sonnet-4-5 (or whichever sonnet-thinking variant you have access to) model, use this meta-prompt first, then paste each numbered prompt above one at a time:

I am rebuilding a suite of browser-only image and data tools from scratch.
All tools run entirely on the client — no backend, no upload, no signup.
The stack is: vanilla HTML5, ES modules, Web Workers, Canvas API,
WebAssembly (via CDN-loaded libraries), and CSS custom properties.
Ground rules for every file you write:
  1. No build step, no bundler — all files run directly from a local HTTP server.
  2. Use ES module syntax (import/export, type="module") except for UMD
     libraries loaded via <script src=…> tags.
  3. All CDN libraries are loaded from unpkg.com or cdn.jsdelivr.net.
     Pin exact versions. No integrity hashes on CDN-fetched ML models
     (they are binary and too large to hash reliably in HTML).
  4. No inline event handlers (onclick=…). Wire all events in JS.
  5. Accessibility: every interactive element has an accessible name.
     Use aria-live="polite" on status regions. Keyboard navigable.
  6. Responsive: works at 320 px width. CSS Grid / Flexbox, no float layout.
  7. Dark theme throughout (see styles in Prompt 0).
  8. Write complete, production-ready files — no TODO comments,
     no placeholder functions, no abbreviated sections.
I will give you one prompt per tool. Think through the architecture
carefully before writing code. For each file, write it in full.
Then paste prompts 0 → 1 → 2 → 3 → 4 → 5 in order, waiting for each to complete before sending the next. Prompt 5 (passport photo) is the most complex — give the model extra budget to think through the MediaPipe integration, worker message protocol, and the JPEG padding approach before it starts writing.